                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Late medieval or early modern binding. Dark brown leather over wooden boards. 4 double raised bands and endbands. Originally two hooked clasps. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, upper part of cover in black ink by a medieval hand what appears to be the same text as on <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>, but difficult to read. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 155</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="310" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="230" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="65" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Complex blind tooled and stamped decoration consisting of panels filled with vegetative motifs.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather heavily worn. Clasps missing. The board on the back cover appears cracked. Newer leather on spine, but this leather is also worn and the spine cracked.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName cert="low" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate when="1331">1331</origDate>. Dating based on colophon on <locus from="162v" to="162v" scheme="folios"/>, where it is also stated that the manuscript was written in a monastery under the abbot <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102672">Hermannus</persName>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Early provenance unknown. A note in German on the <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> (and the same on <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>) mentions that the manuscript is the property of the <quote>cantzlei</quote>, a chancery. This places the manuscript in the German realm, but unclear where. It may have been taken as spoils of war or purchased by Queen Christina, since it is listed in Vossius's catalogue of 1651 (U 212:1, p. 54).The label attached to <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/> refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e) where it is listed as:<quote> Theol. in fol. no 55</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
